    value: 形
english:
  title: Postscript to the Edict Received by Lord Lin, Coadjutor of the National Academy
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Classical learning and the study of words—both are weighty matters for the scholar. The Way of the sage is inscribed in the Six Classics; when one can penetrate the texts of the Six Classics, one thereby illuminates the Way of the sage, and its benefit extends to bringing fortune to this world and its people. Though the study of words carries importance, it cannot compare to classical learning.

    In ancient times, Confucius selected and established the Six Classics through his teachings. In later ages, the many scholars—Zheng Kangcheng, Kong Yingda, and their fellows—vied to elaborate upon them, numbering over eight hundred in all, their writings exceeding a thousand volumes. Students may labor from childhood until their hair turns white, yet some never grasp the essential thread. How much less can we expect complete mastery? Occasionally there appear those who cherish the remnants of the sages' wisdom and recognize the value of ancient texts, who burn the midnight oil year upon year, wearing their lips thin and exhausting their spirit—yet when asked about the transmission of emperors and kings, or the subtle mysteries of human nature and virtue, they reply, "I do not know." Is it any wonder that warriors and vulgar officials dismiss them with ridicule? These are mere phrase-hunters, moldy pedants—not the classical learning of which I speak.

    Lord Lin, Coadjutor of the National Academy, studied under Master Kim Mun, Director of the Jiphyeonjeon. Master Kim studied under Master Lee Yangming, Supervisor of Ritual Arts. Master Lee learned beneath the doors of the Mokeuijeong, the Poeun, the Doeun, and the Yangchon—masters who devoted themselves to the Way of the sage with profound attainment and personal realization. He taught: "Between heaven and earth, nothing surpasses the mysteries of the Five Phases' transformations; when one gathers in one's vision and returns to the beginning, a great thunder sounds." Thus he pursued investigation with all his strength, not confining himself to the commentaries of the Six Classics, but extending his reach to the hundred schools of thought, verifying and scrutinizing whatever shed light upon the meaning of the Classics.

    Lord Lin's learning comes truly from Master Kim, yet is even more vast. In those depths where mystery and subtlety meet, he has illuminated what former scholars did not reach.

    The Six Classics' texts are the words of the sage. The sage understood these truths in his heart, practiced them in his person, and applied them in his works. He wished that rulers and ministers of all ages would follow what he himself had experienced directly. Thus in recording the governance of the Two Emperors and Three Kings appear the instruction of the Canons; in setting forth the rectification of human relations and nature appear the sounds of the Odes; to exalt the Way of Kings and reject the methods of tyrants, the Spring and Autumn was composed; to develop all things and accomplish the tasks of the world, the Changes was annotated. All the great principles for governing the world lie here.

    Therefore I say: when one can penetrate the Six Classics' texts, one understands the Way of the sage; when one understands the Way of the sage, one necessarily grasps how to illuminate the principles of governance. Let a ruler apply these teachings and he shall hear the way to peace and honor; let his ministers follow and they shall learn the perfected methods of the sages. Thus do I hold Lord Lin's classical learning in such regard.

    Once, Master Shen Gong established the Han dynasty's four centuries through a single word of earnest practice. Lord Lin, receiving our Sage Sovereign's invitation of honor, was especially granted an audience. He first expounded the meaning of the Classics, opening the source of holy learning through the principles of rectifying the mind and making the will sincere. When commanded to serve as master to the crown prince, he again unfolded these principles in detail, refining the students' character. Lord Lin's conduct—whether advancing or retiring—accords with righteousness; his speech and writing do not betray his lifelong study. Thus does he establish the foundation for our nation's peace and ten thousand generations of harmony. Can this not be called the great fortune of this age and its people? Surely he deserves to be honored throughout his time and called a great gentleman.

    Lord Lin had the imperial edict mounted as a scroll. The two prime ministers arranged for Lord Seo to write a colophon at its end. One day he brought it to show me, requesting a postscript. I thus recorded how classical learning benefits the world in ways that mere words cannot capture, and praised how the lord, meeting our enlightened sovereign, has brought his learning to full effect.

    Alas, the Way of the sage shines bright as sun and moon; its benefit nourishes humanity as clothing and grain sustain the body. Should one truly carry out these teachings in the governance of all under heaven, there is nothing so lofty or difficult that it cannot be done. It depends only upon the moment of resolve—whether one grasps or releases. Yet I know not whether Lord Lin spoke such words before his teacher.
  footnotes:
    - The reference to 'eight hundred scholars' and 'thousand volumes' is hyperbolic, emphasizing the vast accumulation of classical commentary and the difficulty of mastering it all.
    - The 'two emperors and three kings' refers to the sage-rulers of ancient China—Yao, Shun, Yu, Tang, and King Wen—whose exemplary governance is recorded in the Classics.
    - The phrase 'burning the midnight oil' (焚膏繼晷) is a classical idiom meaning to study intensively through day and night.
    - '''Five Phases'' transformations'' (五行運化) refers to the cosmic principle of wood, fire, earth, metal, and water and their constant transformations—a key concept in Chinese cosmology and the foundation for understanding the Changes.'
    - Master Shen Gong was summoned in old age by the Han emperor, who asked about the Way of learning. Shen replied that true learning lies not in many words but in earnest practice—a principle Kim Su-on invokes to validate Lord Lin's approach to the Classics.
